{
  "texts": [
    "In molecular property prediction, Wu et al. (2023) utilize GNNs to analyze the atomic structure of molecules by representing atoms as nodes and bonds as edges.",
    "The authors use Substructure-Mask Explanation (SME), which identifies crucial substructures within molecules that are key to the model's predictions on molecular properties such as aqueous solubility, genotoxicity, cardiotoxicity, and bloodbrain barrier permeability (Ansari et al. 2022).",
    "GNNs are also known for their efficacy in bioinformatics (Khemani et al. 2024) for tasks like protein folding prediction, where amino acids in a protein sequence are nodes, and their proximities are modeled as edges.",
    "The strength of GNNs lies in their ability to capture complex relationships and interactions between nodes (atoms) and edges (bonds), which is crucial for understanding the intricate structure-property relationships within molecules.",
    "By applying the principles of SME and GNNs, paleontologists can develop models that consider fossils as graphs where different fossil sub-components or fragmented fossils are nodes and their physical or historical connections (e.g., anatomical alignments, shared stratigraphic positions) are edges."
  ]
}